{
  "domain_summary": "The cybersecurity domain in early 2026 is characterized by an accelerated threat landscape where zero-day exploits are increasingly weaponized within 5 days of discovery, compared to 32 days historically. Critical vulnerabilities like CVE-2026-2441 (Chrome) and CVE-2026-22769 (Dell RecoverPoint) are being actively exploited by nation-state actors, prompting emergency patches from major vendors and binding directives from CISA. However, vulnerability research is constrained by opaque embargo systems where CVE publication timelines and vendor-specific disclosure durations remain largely proprietary, creating information asymmetries between defenders and threat actors. While CVE volumes continue growing (21,500+ in H1 2025), the fundamental challenge is not discovery but the 5-45 day gaps between active exploitation and public disclosure of technical details.",
